# Realtime SSE Conventions

## Why SSE, Not WebSocket

CentrAI-Chat uses SSE for streaming because the chat pattern is unidirectional: user sends a message (HTTP POST), server streams tokens back (SSE). This matches how LLM providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini) stream natively. No extra dependencies, no sticky sessions, no Socket.IO.

## API Pattern

The chat endpoint `POST /api/v1/chat/messages` returns an SSE stream:

```typescript
res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/event-stream');
res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
res.setHeader('Connection', 'keep-alive');
res.setHeader('X-Accel-Buffering', 'no');
```

Each event is a JSON object on a `data:` line, double-newline terminated:

```
data: {"event":"token","data":{"content":"Hello"}}\n\n
data: {"event":"done","data":{"messageId":"...","usage":{...}}}\n\n
```

## Event Types

All defined in `packages/types/src/events.ts`:

| Event | When | Payload |
|-------|------|---------|
| `token` | Each streamed token | `{ content: string }` |
| `done` | Stream complete | `{ messageId, usage? }` |
| `error` | Provider or internal error | `{ code, message }` |
| `stopped` | User cancelled | `{ messageId, content }` |

## Cancellation

- Server tracks active streams by message ID via `AbortController`
- `POST /api/v1/chat/messages/:id/stop` triggers abort
- Client receives a `stopped` event with accumulated content

## Client Pattern

Use `fetch()` + `ReadableStream` (not `EventSource`) because we need POST + auth headers:

```typescript
const res = await fetch(url, { method: 'POST', headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` }, body });
const reader = res.body.getReader();
// Parse SSE lines from chunks
```

## Rules

- Never use `EventSource` for chat (it only supports GET, no auth headers).
- Always set `X-Accel-Buffering: no` to prevent nginx from buffering SSE.
- Always send `X-Message-Id` header so clients can call the stop endpoint.
- Event payloads must match the Zod schemas in `@centrai/types/events.ts`.
- Flush headers immediately after setting SSE headers (`res.flushHeaders()`).
